Intellectual / algorithmic ancestry and prior art (credit, not affiliation)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

tracelin is an offline (post-hoc) falsifier over *recorded* multi-agent
execution traces. It stands on decades of distributed-systems verification
and recent multi-agent-systems research. We credit:

- Linearizability and the sequential-consistency / consistency lattice:
  Herlihy & Wing, "Linearizability: A Correctness Condition for Concurrent
  Objects" (TOPLAS 1990). Lamport, "Time, Clocks, and the Ordering of Events
  in a Distributed System" (CACM 1978) — happens-before / logical clocks.

- Practical linearizability checkers we draw algorithmic inspiration from:
  Knossos / Jepsen (Kyle Kingsbury), Porcupine (Anish Athalye),
  Elle (Kingsbury & Alvaro). Wing & Gong / Lowe linearizability search.
  These are databases/registers tools (Go/Clojure); tracelin re-targets the
  ideas to agent traces. No code is copied from them.

- MAST: "Multi-Agent System Failure Taxonomy", Cemri et al., arXiv:2503.13657.
  tracelin maps witnesses to a MAST failure-mode category (FC1–FC3) via a small
  MANUAL table; it does NOT claim mode-level IDs or exhaustive MAST coverage —
  unmapped findings are reported as UNMAPPED.

- "Structural race condition" terminology and the runtime-prevention
  counterpart: S-Bus, "Automatic Read-Set Reconstruction for Multi-Agent LLM
  State Coordination", Khan, arXiv:2605.17076. S-Bus prevents structural race
  conditions at runtime (HTTP middleware); tracelin *detects* them offline in
  recorded traces. Complementary, not competing.

- General concurrent-systems trace validation (neighbor, not the same scope):
  OmniLink, "Trace Validation of Unmodified Concurrent Systems",
  arXiv:2601.11836 (validates databases / lock-free structures against TLA+;
  not agent-trace specific).

- OpenTelemetry GenAI semantic conventions and the A2A task lifecycle inform
  the trace data model and the a2a_lifecycle conformance spec.

Witness minimisation: a greedy 1-minimisation in the delta-debugging tradition
of Zeller & Hildebrandt, "Simplifying and Isolating Failure-Inducing Input"
(ddmin) — the result is 1-minimal, though the search is single-element greedy
rather than ddmin's partition-granularity algorithm.
